00:16:33,479 --> 00:16:33,599
future.

249
00:16:33,599 --> 00:16:37,742
They wanted a game that was closer to today's life.

250
00:16:37,742 --> 00:16:40,164
Also the 2030s really excited us.

251
00:16:40,164 --> 00:16:44,528
When we looked at the timeline for the first Deus Ex, we saw that the 2030s was the time

252
00:16:44,528 --> 00:16:49,873
when mechanical augmentations were introduced and that brought a lot of turmoil.

253
00:16:49,873 --> 00:16:54,276
It was a theme that really, really excited us.

254
00:16:55,867 --> 00:16:58,207
And finally, we thought it would be easier for new players

255
00:16:58,207 --> 00:17:00,488
to get into the franchise, if you don't have to play

256
00:17:00,488 --> 00:17:03,948
the other two games before,

257
00:17:03,948 --> 00:17:05,669
and you just have this one to play.

258
00:17:05,669 --> 00:17:09,690
And afterwards, you can go back and play the other games

259
00:17:09,690 --> 00:17:11,790
if you wanna see how it is.

260
00:17:11,790 --> 00:17:12,030
References.

261
00:17:12,030 --> 00:17:17,351
We used references as a common language.

262
00:17:17,351 --> 00:17:20,932
It was easier for us to talk about abstracts,

263
00:17:20,932 --> 00:17:24,433
such as mood, if we had references, concrete references.

264
00:17:24,965 --> 00:17:30,967
to use, it was also a way for us to communicate our examples, our ideas, sorry.

265
00:17:30,967 --> 00:17:38,108
So this is our main reference for the game, for the tone of it, and then we had references

266
00:17:38,108 --> 00:17:39,929
for every single gameplay pillar.

267
00:17:39,929 --> 00:17:47,270
And for every reference, we also wrote what we wanted in each, like saying that fear is

268
00:17:47,270 --> 00:17:51,652
a reference, it's maybe too large, so we wanted fear for its AI for example.

269
00:17:58,857 --> 00:18:03,920
So, yeah, social, tone of the game, and conspiracies.

270
00:18:03,920 --> 00:18:08,983
Yes, thank you, David.

271
00:18:08,983 --> 00:18:13,566
Before we ended Conception,

272
00:18:13,566 --> 00:18:16,027
we also had figured out all our gameplay loops.

273
00:18:16,027 --> 00:18:20,950
So, we pretty knew early on what kind of game

274
00:18:20,950 --> 00:18:21,691
we were building.

275
00:18:22,252 --> 00:18:27,374
And for each gameplay loop, we also had explanations for everything.

276
00:18:27,374 --> 00:18:30,536
Just so, there were directions, there were intentions.

277
00:18:30,536 --> 00:18:34,278
I got a lot of text here, I'm going to skip through everything.

278
00:18:34,278 --> 00:18:42,381
I just want to show you the amount of details that we had before we left Conception.

279
00:18:42,381 --> 00:18:48,224
We often hear about projects that go in pre-prod, and they don't really know where they're going,

280
00:18:48,224 --> 00:18:50,225
and they're trying to find their gameplay.

281
00:18:50,865 --> 00:18:54,267
And we knew before going pre-prod

282
00:18:54,267 --> 00:18:56,108
exactly what we wanted to do

283
00:18:56,108 --> 00:19:00,150
and what each system was supposed to do in the game.

284
00:19:00,150 --> 00:19:03,071
Combat and stealth.

285
00:19:03,071 --> 00:19:03,812
And hacking.

286
00:19:03,812 --> 00:19:04,212
And social.

287
00:19:04,212 --> 00:19:05,313
I'm sorry if I skip through this quickly.

288
00:19:22,999 --> 00:19:25,000
And finally, towards the end of conception,

289
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:27,281
we got what we call detailed system directions.

290
00:19:27,281 --> 00:19:31,184
So for each system, we would say exactly

291
00:19:31,184 --> 00:19:34,386
what the system needed to do.

292
00:19:34,386 --> 00:19:37,669
And that was a direction for game designers to hit.

293
00:19:37,669 --> 00:19:40,691
And it was also a way for the creative director

