00:19:40,691 --> 00:19:44,633
to judge if a final design done during pre-prod

295
00:19:44,633 --> 00:19:46,515
would pass or not.

296
00:19:46,515 --> 00:19:49,276
So we knew exactly what we were doing

297
00:19:49,276 --> 00:19:50,517
and what we were supposed to...

298
00:19:51,504 --> 00:19:52,805
to go with each system.

299
00:19:52,805 --> 00:19:56,788
This is the one for combat and continued,

300
00:19:56,788 --> 00:19:57,928
and one for stealth.

301
00:19:57,928 --> 00:20:03,693
So already we're talking about feedback and

302
00:20:03,693 --> 00:20:07,035
augmentations and cover.

303
00:20:07,035 --> 00:20:07,996
And hacking.

304
00:20:07,996 --> 00:20:08,216
And social.

305
00:20:21,575 --> 00:20:26,924
By the end of conception, everything I've shown you so far, we put on huge sheets of paper,

306
00:20:26,924 --> 00:20:31,391
which we papered the walls over with. And this was very important.

307
00:20:31,890 --> 00:20:34,711
The first reason is that we could not ignore it.

308
00:20:34,711 --> 00:20:39,953
If you have a design that you put on an Excel sheet

309
00:20:39,953 --> 00:20:42,754
or a Word document, and you just put it on the server

310
00:20:42,754 --> 00:20:45,575
and you forget about it, then you're not gonna follow

311
00:20:45,575 --> 00:20:47,876
exactly what you wanted to do at the beginning.

312
00:20:47,876 --> 00:20:51,517
So by having it on walls, every single morning

313
00:20:51,517 --> 00:20:54,818
when we came in, we saw exactly what we needed to do.

314
00:20:54,818 --> 00:20:56,739
And also while working during the day,

315
00:20:56,739 --> 00:21:00,100
we just looked up and we could see exactly

316
00:21:00,100 --> 00:21:01,341
what we needed to do.

317
00:21:02,309 --> 00:21:03,429
They were so important in fact,

318
00:21:03,429 --> 00:21:05,970
that when we moved to our final offices,

319
00:21:05,970 --> 00:21:07,551
it's the first thing we put up.

320
00:21:07,551 --> 00:21:16,434
And they were there until we did not need them anymore.

321
00:21:16,434 --> 00:21:20,316
So I really think that having this kind of detail

322
00:21:20,316 --> 00:21:21,677
was crucial.

323
00:21:22,062 --> 00:21:25,463
to bring the gameplay that we did for Human Revolution.

324
00:21:25,463 --> 00:21:29,064
We did not search during pre-prod

325
00:21:29,064 --> 00:21:31,164
to know what the game would be.

326
00:21:31,164 --> 00:21:33,885
We did not redo systems.

327
00:21:33,885 --> 00:21:35,585
We did not rethink the game.

328
00:21:35,585 --> 00:21:37,565
We just went full speed ahead.

329
00:21:37,565 --> 00:21:39,866
We knew exactly what we wanted this game to be,

330
00:21:39,866 --> 00:21:41,506
what we wanted the player to feel.

331
00:21:41,506 --> 00:21:46,827
And the whole team was with us until the end.

332
00:21:46,827 --> 00:21:48,568
Now before I go on to pre-production,

333
00:21:48,568 --> 00:21:51,588
I want to talk about the way we work during conception.

334
00:21:53,023 --> 00:21:56,044
We worked in a way we called the creative core.

335
00:21:56,044 --> 00:21:57,184
And that means that...

336
00:21:57,184 --> 00:22:02,066
All right, it fell off again.

337
00:22:02,066 --> 00:22:05,847
That means that the creative director

338
00:22:05,847 --> 00:22:07,848
was not the one to come down from the mountain

339
00:22:07,848 --> 00:22:12,710
with the design and say...

340
00:22:12,710 --> 00:22:14,170
Sorry.

341
00:22:14,924 --> 00:22:18,467
So the creative director was not the one to come down from the mountain and tell us,

342
00:22:18,467 --> 00:22:21,450
this is the game I want to do, follow my lead.

343
00:22:21,450 --> 00:22:28,876
Instead, everybody on the team had a say about our ideas or what we wanted to do.

344
00:22:28,876 --> 00:22:33,180
And not to say that we did the design through consensus,

345
00:22:33,180 --> 00:22:38,605
because sometimes people had ideas and they weren't incorporated into the design.

346
00:22:38,605 --> 00:22:42,368
But it was done in such a way as to everybody had a say.

347
00:22:43,518 --> 00:22:47,920
and everybody was kind of equal with JF, the creative director, being a referee.

348
00:22:47,920 --> 00:22:54,244
This meant that an idea would only survive if it was really good.

349
00:22:54,244 --> 00:22:56,405
And it also meant that we got...

350
00:22:57,017 --> 00:23:00,098
a sense of attachment to the game.

351
00:23:00,098 --> 00:23:02,439
It was not something that was handed down to us,

352
00:23:02,439 --> 00:23:05,140
it was something everybody had a hand in.

353
00:23:05,140 --> 00:23:08,562
So it was a lot easier for us to really pour ourselves

354
00:23:08,562 --> 00:23:11,143
into this game during pre-prod and production.

355
00:23:11,143 --> 00:23:14,184
I fully credit this as a big part of why

356
00:23:14,184 --> 00:23:16,966
I think the game kind of has a soul.

357
00:23:16,966 --> 00:23:18,987
It feels special when you play it,

358
00:23:18,987 --> 00:23:21,448
and I think that's part of the reason for it.

359
00:23:21,448 --> 00:23:21,888
Pre-production.

360
00:23:26,810 --> 00:23:28,870
The blueprint process.

361
00:23:28,870 --> 00:23:30,610
Blueprint was a way for us to chart

362
00:23:30,610 --> 00:23:32,171
the whole game in advance.

363
00:23:32,171 --> 00:23:34,531
In there you could see all the locations

364
00:23:34,531 --> 00:23:36,672
that would be visited and in which order,

365
00:23:36,672 --> 00:23:39,252
all the conversations that would be part of it,

366
00:23:39,252 --> 00:23:42,833
the choices given to the player and the consequences.

367
00:23:42,833 --> 00:23:44,473
I'm not gonna go in detail about that

368
00:23:44,473 --> 00:23:47,534
because Mary DeMar, our narrative designer,

369
00:23:47,534 --> 00:23:50,594
already did a talk at GDC Austin last year.

370
00:23:50,594 --> 00:23:52,635
And the talk is called

371
00:23:52,635 --> 00:23:54,275
Building the Story-Driven Experience

372
00:23:54,275 --> 00:23:55,975
of Deer Sex Human Revolution.

373
00:23:56,315 --> 00:24:02,919
So if you want to know more about Blueprint, I would suggest that you go to the GDC Austin website and download our PowerPoint.

