00:24:12,505 --> 00:24:22,230
So it was pretty big, but it was invaluable to know exactly where everything went and to get a sense of the flow for the overall game.

376
00:24:22,230 --> 00:24:24,972
Conversation system.

377
00:24:28,939 --> 00:24:34,084
The idea behind the conversation system was to have a relationship between the player's choice

378
00:24:34,084 --> 00:24:39,409
and the consequences to that choice not being explicit.

379
00:24:39,409 --> 00:24:42,952
We wanted people to try and read the characters

380
00:24:42,952 --> 00:24:48,016
and to make a choice based on the character's personality and demeanor.

381
00:24:48,016 --> 00:24:54,642
At that time, we didn't know about L.A. Noire.

382
00:24:56,065 --> 00:25:01,669
So, yeah, the idea is, let's say you have a character with a weak personality,

383
00:25:01,669 --> 00:25:06,572
but he would come at you with anger, then you would try and smack him down

384
00:25:06,572 --> 00:25:11,595
and you would know that he would kind of come back and say,

385
00:25:11,595 --> 00:25:14,257
okay, okay, you win, you win.

386
00:25:15,400 --> 00:25:17,301
And there was a lot of tension on the team,

387
00:25:17,301 --> 00:25:20,423
because a lot of people thought that the system was too murky.

388
00:25:20,423 --> 00:25:23,785
They told us, how are we supposed

389
00:25:23,785 --> 00:25:25,546
to make good decisions as a player

390
00:25:25,546 --> 00:25:27,708
if we don't know what's going on,

391
00:25:27,708 --> 00:25:30,569
or if we don't have good feedback?

392
00:25:30,569 --> 00:25:33,191
And their opinions were valid, but it turns out

393
00:25:33,191 --> 00:25:36,513
that players really liked it, because they thought it mimicked

394
00:25:36,513 --> 00:25:37,333
a real conversation.

395
00:25:37,333 --> 00:25:39,175
A real conversation is uncertain.

396
00:25:39,175 --> 00:25:41,236
You don't know what's going to happen.

397
00:25:41,236 --> 00:25:43,397
And that's kind of what we tried to do with this.

398
00:25:45,927 --> 00:25:51,652
The conversations were really costly, animation-wise and also because of recording.

399
00:25:51,652 --> 00:25:56,595
So we didn't want to just go ahead, write a conversation and implement it.

400
00:25:56,595 --> 00:25:57,976
We needed to test it first.

401
00:25:57,976 --> 00:26:05,482
And that's why we used an Excel sheet with macros to do the full gameplay before we did

402
00:26:05,482 --> 00:26:07,184
any code or any animations.

403
00:26:07,184 --> 00:26:13,528
You can see in the bottom left corner, the boxes there, is essentially the gameplay.

404
00:26:14,103 --> 00:26:20,345
It was a simple rock, paper, scissor thing where the player had three choices of attack

405
00:26:20,345 --> 00:26:34,771
and the NPC would select at random a counter and you needed to guess which was the correct answer.

406
00:26:34,771 --> 00:26:40,633
Is something wrong? Okay. Okay. I'm sorry.

407
00:26:47,099 --> 00:26:49,323
Okay, yeah, it's better.

408
00:26:49,323 --> 00:26:50,144
Good?

409
00:26:50,144 --> 00:26:59,440
So, yeah, attacks and countâ€”oh, a bit loud, though.

410
00:27:00,449 --> 00:27:01,750
It acts in counters, so yes.

411
00:27:01,750 --> 00:27:06,034
The gameplay would check whether you had one attack

412
00:27:06,034 --> 00:27:08,436
that was weak against a counter,

413
00:27:08,436 --> 00:27:09,597
strong against another one,

414
00:27:09,597 --> 00:27:11,379
and neutral against the last one.

415
00:27:11,379 --> 00:27:14,882
And then the rest of the gameplay was the writers

416
00:27:14,882 --> 00:27:18,244
attempting to steer you to the correct answer

417
00:27:18,244 --> 00:27:20,707
without giving away the farm.

418
00:27:20,707 --> 00:27:24,069
Which wasn't easy, but the Excel sheet really helped us.

419
00:27:25,540 --> 00:27:32,144
this is a conversation pane. What we did is we would put the conversation in Excel and we would

420
00:27:32,144 --> 00:27:38,128
take the file and send it to everybody on the dev team. And the conversation has a timer so it

421
00:27:38,128 --> 00:27:42,711
evolved in real time. You would have, this is the conversation with Wayne from Detroit's

422
00:27:42,711 --> 00:27:47,454
police station. And you would have Wayne actually talk to you in real time with each line

423
00:27:47,454 --> 00:27:52,577
appearing. And you would select one of the three choices and at the end you would get a pop-up

424
00:27:52,577 --> 00:27:54,758
that would tell you if you wanted a conversation or not.

425
00:27:57,207 --> 00:28:02,709
In the background, the Excel sheet would check all the players' answers,

426
00:28:02,709 --> 00:28:07,210
and then the players would send us back the file with comments.

427
00:28:07,210 --> 00:28:11,871
They would tell us if they liked the conversation, if they understood anything.

428
00:28:11,871 --> 00:28:14,212
Sometimes they didn't, so we had to rewrite stuff.

429
00:28:15,253 --> 00:28:18,355
And then we would do a tally of all the answers we got.

430
00:28:18,355 --> 00:28:22,118
We waited until we got about 40 answers,

431
00:28:22,118 --> 00:28:25,681
just to make sure that we didn't base our decisions

432
00:28:25,681 --> 00:28:26,421
on not enough data.

433
00:28:26,421 --> 00:28:29,344
And then we would tally everything and see trends.

434
00:28:29,344 --> 00:28:33,127
We could see how many people won the conversation,

435
00:28:33,127 --> 00:28:35,528
how many lost, at which round,

436
00:28:35,528 --> 00:28:38,771
just to have a sense of which counter was unclear

437
00:28:38,771 --> 00:28:41,393
or which player attack was maybe too precise.

438
00:28:41,393 --> 00:28:43,815
Because if everybody won the conversation,

439
00:28:43,815 --> 00:28:44,215
then there were...

440
00:28:44,995 --> 00:28:45,836
then we had a problem.

441
00:28:45,836 --> 00:28:49,856
But if nobody understood it, we also had a problem.

442
00:28:49,856 --> 00:28:54,718
We did rewrite a whole conversation based on these results,

443
00:28:54,718 --> 00:28:57,158
but usually it was only parts that we would rewrite,

444
00:28:57,158 --> 00:28:58,478
probably like a round or two.

445
00:28:58,478 --> 00:29:04,500
And once we did the changes, we sent the Excel sheet back,

446
00:29:04,500 --> 00:29:07,460
but this time to another group, oftentimes testers.

447
00:29:09,440 --> 00:29:11,741
The hacking system, yes, okay, this is good

448
00:29:11,741 --> 00:29:14,783
because nobody has ever seen this.

449
00:29:14,783 --> 00:29:18,866
The hacking system also started in Excel.

450
00:29:18,866 --> 00:29:23,349
I had this vision of a high-fidelity hacking.

451
00:29:24,138 --> 00:29:28,140
where you would really feel like you were a hacker.

452
00:29:28,140 --> 00:29:30,001
So we prototyped it using Excel,

453
00:29:30,001 --> 00:29:31,842
and we tried to prototype the whole experience,

454
00:29:31,842 --> 00:29:33,743
not just the mechanics.

455
00:29:33,743 --> 00:29:37,625
So the player was first tasked to select a port

456
00:29:37,625 --> 00:29:39,806
by which he wanted to connect to the computer.

457
00:29:40,633 --> 00:29:45,115
And then the ports would have attributes such as a lifespan.

458
00:29:45,115 --> 00:29:47,516
A port could maybe close after a minute or so.

459
00:29:47,516 --> 00:29:48,957
You also had traffic speed.

460
00:29:48,957 --> 00:29:54,120
The more traffic, the longer it takes to download stuff off the computer and also protection.

461
00:29:54,120 --> 00:29:57,221
So a port with high protection would be harder to break.

462
00:29:57,221 --> 00:30:03,844
And then you could go on the computer and you could see stuff that was on it before

463
00:30:03,844 --> 00:30:05,705
you actually attempted to hack it.

464
00:30:08,258 --> 00:30:10,680
This is the interface for the original hacking.

465
00:30:10,680 --> 00:30:12,461
It's not the one that's in the game right now.

466
00:30:12,461 --> 00:30:13,841
It's our first attempt.

467
00:30:13,841 --> 00:30:18,204
You can see on the left that the boxes are the integrity.

468
00:30:18,204 --> 00:30:20,785
The idea was that the player would use programs

469
00:30:20,785 --> 00:30:22,966
to attack a network's integrity

470
00:30:22,966 --> 00:30:25,328
while the network was trying to see

471
00:30:25,328 --> 00:30:26,608
if there was anybody there.

472
00:30:26,608 --> 00:30:28,029
And if, once you were detected,

473
00:30:28,029 --> 00:30:29,250
it would try to trace you

474
00:30:29,250 --> 00:30:32,712
and then send reinforcements in the form of guards.

475
00:30:33,507 --> 00:30:38,012
And at the bottom we have the three programs that the player had.

476
00:30:38,012 --> 00:30:43,778
And the gameplay was about taking CPU cycles from your computer

477
00:30:43,778 --> 00:30:46,421
and assigning them to each of the three programs.

478
00:30:46,421 --> 00:30:49,765
You had the attack program that would bring down the integrity.

479
00:30:49,765 --> 00:30:53,409
You also had the stealth program that would prevent the network from detecting you.

480
00:30:53,849 --> 00:30:57,715
And finally defend would make the trace longer.

481
00:30:57,715 --> 00:30:59,237
And you had to assign these cycles,

482
00:30:59,237 --> 00:31:01,600
so if you put all your cycles in attack,

483
00:31:01,600 --> 00:31:03,463
the integrity would go down really fast,

484
00:31:03,463 --> 00:31:05,025
but then it would be super easy

485
00:31:05,025 --> 00:31:06,006
for the network to detect you.

486
00:31:09,795 --> 00:31:14,161
That's not all. The player was also supposed to look at a map

487
00:31:14,161 --> 00:31:18,767
because we wanted hacking to occur in the world. So we

488
00:31:18,767 --> 00:31:22,873
designed this map with the red dot over there is a guard and

489
00:31:22,873 --> 00:31:24,435
you're the green square.

490
00:31:25,135 --> 00:31:28,337
And we had this guard just running along in the corridor,

491
00:31:28,337 --> 00:31:30,477
but at some point he would come in the room.

492
00:31:30,477 --> 00:31:32,398
So while you were hacking, there was a button

493
00:31:32,398 --> 00:31:34,979
on the Excel sheet where you could go to the map

494
00:31:34,979 --> 00:31:35,879
and see where the guard is.

495
00:31:35,879 --> 00:31:38,040
And once he came into the room,

496
00:31:38,040 --> 00:31:41,161
you had buttons to change location.

497
00:31:41,161 --> 00:31:44,563
So this was to see if players would be able to hack

498
00:31:44,563 --> 00:31:46,303
while also looking around their environment.

499
00:31:49,579 --> 00:31:52,082
And finally, once you managed to hack the system,

500
00:31:52,082 --> 00:31:54,845
you had access to everything that was on it,

501
00:31:54,845 --> 00:31:56,627
but you had to download it first.

502
00:31:56,627 --> 00:31:59,731
So you were waiting for stuff to download

503
00:31:59,731 --> 00:32:01,593
while there was nothing to do.

504
00:32:01,593 --> 00:32:05,197
And this is the result, nice email.

505
00:32:17,457 --> 00:32:19,258
And of course, David is totally right.

506
00:32:19,258 --> 00:32:22,119
This was way too complicated.

507
00:32:22,119 --> 00:32:25,902
This is one of the pains that I used

508
00:32:25,902 --> 00:32:28,743
to try and configure the gameplay.

509
00:32:28,743 --> 00:32:29,864
This is the other one.

510
00:32:29,864 --> 00:32:32,325
At some point, it was so complicated

511
00:32:32,325 --> 00:32:35,167
that I didn't even know what I was doing.

512
00:32:37,014 --> 00:32:40,776
The problem with the system is we asked too much of the player.

513
00:32:40,776 --> 00:32:46,140
Having CPU cycles was too abstract.

514
00:32:46,140 --> 00:32:48,261
Having to look at the map was just too much.

515
00:32:48,261 --> 00:32:54,446
And then asking the player to wait to download stuff, people, they just couldn't handle that.

516
00:32:56,242 --> 00:33:02,866
So but I really wanted that system. I was really fighting for it. And JF, my boss, he had me

517
00:33:02,866 --> 00:33:09,190
redesign it three times. But still it wasn't enough. I was sure at some point I would finally

518
00:33:09,190 --> 00:33:13,413
crack the code. But I guess it never came.

519
00:33:15,197 --> 00:33:18,139
This is a, yeah, you could even upgrade your everything.

520
00:33:18,139 --> 00:33:19,901
You could upgrade your CPU cycles

521
00:33:19,901 --> 00:33:21,502
and you could upgrade your programs.

522
00:33:21,502 --> 00:33:24,285
And the zombie thing, once you hack the computer,

523
00:33:24,285 --> 00:33:25,786
you could put a rootkit on it.

524
00:33:25,786 --> 00:33:28,749
And then when you went to hack another computer,

525
00:33:28,749 --> 00:33:31,492
you could use all the computers you hacked before

526
00:33:31,492 --> 00:33:34,935
with CPU cycles to make your hacking even easier.

527
00:33:34,935 --> 00:33:38,178
So I was really, really hopeful this would work.

528
00:33:38,178 --> 00:33:39,559
I really wanted to play that game.

529
00:33:44,008 --> 00:33:51,191
Yeah, okay. This is a concept art done by Matthew, our interface designer at the time.

530
00:33:51,191 --> 00:33:55,633
He came up with this simple idea. What if we make hacking visual? I was livid. I hated

531
00:33:55,633 --> 00:33:58,314
that guy for a week. But he was right. And at some point, JF looked at me and he just

532
00:33:58,314 --> 00:33:59,955
he had to grab me from the ledge. I was ready to jump.

533
00:34:09,536 --> 00:34:12,698
And he said, look, this is not working out.

534
00:34:12,698 --> 00:34:15,719
I know where you're going, but it's just too complicated.

535
00:34:15,719 --> 00:34:18,360
This will work.

536
00:34:18,360 --> 00:34:19,841
This is the direction.

537
00:34:19,841 --> 00:34:21,982
So just some time.

538
00:34:23,102 --> 00:34:25,383
took some time for me to get around to it.

539
00:34:25,383 --> 00:34:28,485
But eventually I saw that by taking the mechanics

540
00:34:28,485 --> 00:34:31,267
we had in the Excel sheet and just porting them

541
00:34:31,267 --> 00:34:35,610
to this kind of display, like the idea of taking over

542
00:34:35,610 --> 00:34:38,812
a network by slowly degrading integrity

543
00:34:38,812 --> 00:34:41,914
is how essentially you take nodes in the hacking today.

544
00:34:41,914 --> 00:34:44,375
The idea that you could defend stuff

545
00:34:44,375 --> 00:34:46,116
is also part of the hacking.

546
00:34:46,116 --> 00:34:48,498
So all the mechanics I had done in the Excel sheet

547
00:34:48,498 --> 00:34:50,719
turned out to work perfectly with this.

548
00:34:50,719 --> 00:34:52,901
So once I saw that, it took two weeks.

549
00:34:53,261 --> 00:34:56,783
to just port everything and we had our new gameplay.

550
00:34:56,783 --> 00:35:00,165
It went so well, in fact, that

551
00:35:00,165 --> 00:35:05,107
hacking is the first game system that was feature complete

552
00:35:05,107 --> 00:35:06,668
before anything else in the game.

553
00:35:06,668 --> 00:35:08,409
I think two years before we shipped,

554
00:35:08,409 --> 00:35:10,811
hacking was done and we were playing it.

555
00:35:10,811 --> 00:35:11,511
So I'm pretty happy with it now.

556
00:35:11,511 --> 00:35:13,492
I wasn't at the time, though.

557
00:35:13,492 --> 00:35:14,232
Energy system.

558
00:35:14,232 --> 00:35:16,073
Yeah, this one.

559
00:35:16,073 --> 00:35:17,014
This is a good one, too.

560
00:35:23,810 --> 00:35:27,774
For a long time during the game, we did not have an energy system.

561
00:35:27,774 --> 00:35:28,795
Why?

562
00:35:28,795 --> 00:35:31,957
Because we found it frustrating in the first game.

563
00:35:31,957 --> 00:35:36,121
We remembered that while playing it, we were always lacking energy.

564
00:35:36,121 --> 00:35:37,982
We couldn't use our augmentations.

565
00:35:37,982 --> 00:35:41,045
The bar was always empty.

566
00:35:41,045 --> 00:35:44,548
So we thought, we're geniuses, we're not going to put energy in the game.

567
00:35:44,548 --> 00:35:46,530
You use your augmentations whenever you want.

568
00:35:47,555 --> 00:35:49,016
But then the takedowns came.

569
00:35:49,016 --> 00:35:52,459
And we saw that players would do takedowns all the time.

570
00:35:52,459 --> 00:35:54,160
There was no restrictions for them.

571
00:35:55,887 --> 00:35:57,529
They weren't even using weapons anymore.

572
00:35:57,529 --> 00:36:02,233
They would just go and stealth and do takes and everybody would fall down.

573
00:36:02,233 --> 00:36:06,877
So we looked at each other and we said, well, okay, now we understand why there was an energy

574
00:36:06,877 --> 00:36:07,318
system.

575
00:36:07,318 --> 00:36:12,242
So we brought it back, but we decided to use cells instead, instead of a large bar because

576
00:36:12,242 --> 00:36:14,404
we wanted the first cell to always regenerate.

577
00:36:14,404 --> 00:36:16,766
That way the player would always have energy to use.

578
00:36:16,766 --> 00:36:19,028
But still people were complaining.

579
00:36:19,028 --> 00:36:20,109
There's not enough energy.

580
00:36:20,977 --> 00:36:24,038
So Jeff would tell me, put more nutrient bars in the game,

581
00:36:24,038 --> 00:36:25,398
put more nutrient bars in the game.

582
00:36:25,398 --> 00:36:28,220
So I did, but still people were complaining.

583
00:36:28,220 --> 00:36:31,281
But at some point I was resisting it.

584
00:36:31,281 --> 00:36:36,303
And the reason is that

585
00:36:36,303 --> 00:36:40,125
Their Sex is a game about scarcity of resources.

586
00:36:41,733 --> 00:36:44,997
If we give you everything, you're not going to think anymore.

587
00:36:44,997 --> 00:36:48,280
You're just going to go and use the simple route.

588
00:36:48,280 --> 00:36:50,002
If you have all the energy in the world,

589
00:36:50,002 --> 00:36:51,884
you're going to use your stealth augmentation,

590
00:36:51,884 --> 00:36:54,007
your cloaking, all the way through the game,

591
00:36:54,007 --> 00:36:56,710
or you're going to do takedowns like people used to do.

592
00:36:57,234 --> 00:37:02,680
That's why we still have people complaining today there's not enough nutrients in the game.

593
00:37:02,680 --> 00:37:05,463
Well, if you're one of those, I'm the guy to blame.

594
00:37:05,463 --> 00:37:06,764
I'm sorry.

595
00:37:06,764 --> 00:37:10,389
But I think it was really crucial to how the game turned out.

596
00:37:10,389 --> 00:37:14,673
Otherwise, it wouldn't be a dare sex game.

597
00:37:14,673 --> 00:37:17,857
You would just plow through and it would be an action game.

598
00:37:20,329 --> 00:37:25,952
And I find it kind of ironic that the exact things that I didn't like in the first Deus Ex

599
00:37:25,952 --> 00:37:29,534
is something that we essentially brought back in our game.

600
00:37:29,534 --> 00:37:30,034
So, irony. I love it.

601
00:37:30,034 --> 00:37:31,075
Production.

602
00:37:31,075 --> 00:37:31,415
Boss fights.

603
00:37:31,415 --> 00:37:33,156
And I'm not sure I do. Sorry, David.

604
00:37:46,543 --> 00:37:50,046
The problem with boss fights, how can I say that?

605
00:37:50,046 --> 00:37:53,709
Remember the directions sheets I was talking about at the beginning?

606
00:37:53,709 --> 00:37:57,412
We didn't have one for boss fights. We kind of forgot about it.

607
00:37:59,020 --> 00:38:03,063
So just, well it shows how important they were

608
00:38:03,063 --> 00:38:05,744
because we didn't have these direction sheets.

609
00:38:05,744 --> 00:38:09,787
We didn't really know what we were doing with boss fights.

610
00:38:09,787 --> 00:38:12,468
For us, we saw them as a way to break the pacing

611
00:38:12,468 --> 00:38:15,570
more than a way to test the player's skills.

612
00:38:15,570 --> 00:38:20,273
That's a big factor why you cannot go through them

613
00:38:20,273 --> 00:38:21,813
by using social or stealth.

614
00:38:23,070 --> 00:38:29,076
We also waited until the middle of production before we actually tackled them. There was no design during pre-prod

615
00:38:29,076 --> 00:38:33,961
It's during production that we we started design on them. So we were also pressed by time

616
00:38:35,757 --> 00:38:39,978
But we thought that by putting enough ammo and enough weapons in the room,

617
00:38:39,978 --> 00:38:43,499
that would be enough for players to just defeat them and say,

618
00:38:43,499 --> 00:38:48,581
okay, that was nice, let's go on.

619
00:38:48,581 --> 00:38:53,942
And playtests did flag the boss fights as a problem,

620
00:38:53,942 --> 00:38:56,083
but they did not flag the severity of it.

621
00:38:56,083 --> 00:39:00,084
It's only once we shipped and we saw the complaint that we fully understood,

622
00:39:00,084 --> 00:39:01,644
but it was a surprise to us actually.

623
00:39:02,595 --> 00:39:05,176
A big surprise and not a good one.

624
00:39:05,176 --> 00:39:08,317
But, so yeah, I don't really have a solution

625
00:39:08,317 --> 00:39:10,298
regarding boss fights except that next time

626
00:39:10,298 --> 00:39:12,399
we're gonna think about it more.

627
00:39:12,399 --> 00:39:16,461
And we're gonna put, they were a big part of the game

628
00:39:16,461 --> 00:39:18,322
and we should have put more efforts in them.

629
00:39:18,322 --> 00:39:19,782
So, truly sorry about that.

630
00:39:19,782 --> 00:39:20,463
The upgrade system.

631
00:39:30,064 --> 00:39:34,707
At the beginning we had this idea that to upgrade your character you needed to go to a limb clinic.

632
00:39:34,707 --> 00:39:38,350
Adam didn't have all the augmentations.

633
00:39:38,350 --> 00:39:43,734
Stuff like Cassie, the sociolog, or the cloaking stuff was all at a limb clinic

634
00:39:43,734 --> 00:39:48,798
and you had to physically go there and buy these augmentations by using money.

635
00:39:48,798 --> 00:39:53,101
We thought it would be more fun for players and would be more realistic.

636
00:39:54,513 --> 00:39:58,219
Unfortunately, we found out that that's not at all how players

637
00:39:58,219 --> 00:40:01,503
want to play the game. What we saw through playtest was that

638
00:40:01,503 --> 00:40:04,728
players wanted to come up to a challenge and be able to upgrade

639
00:40:04,728 --> 00:40:06,311
right there on the spot.

640
00:40:08,510 --> 00:40:13,073
So they saw a big crate or an impassable stealth challenge

641
00:40:13,073 --> 00:40:15,875
and they said, well, I want the augmentation

642
00:40:15,875 --> 00:40:17,676
to move that crate, or I want the augmentation

643
00:40:17,676 --> 00:40:18,937
to cloak myself.

644
00:40:18,937 --> 00:40:21,899
And by asking them to go to a limb clinic,

645
00:40:21,899 --> 00:40:25,542
we were essentially forcing them to anticipate their needs

646
00:40:25,542 --> 00:40:27,743
before they actually needed anything.

647
00:40:27,743 --> 00:40:30,205
And that wasn't fun, it was counterintuitive.

648
00:40:31,550 --> 00:40:36,735
So we eventually decided to nix that design,

649
00:40:36,735 --> 00:40:39,057
and we put all the augmentations on Atom

650
00:40:39,057 --> 00:40:40,758
at the beginning of the game,

651
00:40:40,758 --> 00:40:44,581
and we allowed players to unlock stuff at their own rhythm.

652
00:40:44,581 --> 00:40:46,863
But of course that broke other stuff,

653
00:40:46,863 --> 00:40:49,565
like the first conversation in the Detroit

654
00:40:49,565 --> 00:40:51,827
manufacturing plant with Zeke Sanders.

655
00:40:52,508 --> 00:40:55,669
was never designed to use CASSI, the social log,

656
00:40:55,669 --> 00:40:59,791
because we knew that the first limb clinic was in Detroit,

657
00:40:59,791 --> 00:41:01,152
which was afterwards.

658
00:41:01,152 --> 00:41:04,573
So there was no way for the player to get the augmentation.

659
00:41:04,573 --> 00:41:06,034
Now it was possible.

660
00:41:06,034 --> 00:41:08,895
So we needed to go through the first parts of the game,

661
00:41:08,895 --> 00:41:10,156
the whole manufacturing plan,

662
00:41:10,156 --> 00:41:12,717
and balance it in a way

663
00:41:12,717 --> 00:41:14,838
where you wouldn't get enough experience points.

664
00:41:15,739 --> 00:41:22,444
to unlock Cassie before you arrived at the Zeke conversation, because Zeke was already done.

665
00:41:22,444 --> 00:41:27,608
Everything was recorded, everything was animated, there was no way for us to just go back and add

666
00:41:27,608 --> 00:41:33,373
the Cassie support. And I'm going to tell you, trying to balance the first level,

667
00:41:33,373 --> 00:41:35,514
just so you wouldn't get Cassie first, was...

668
00:41:36,115 --> 00:41:38,597
a big, big, big challenge and a big problem.

669
00:41:38,597 --> 00:41:40,959
And Mary, our narrative designer, wasn't happy

670
00:41:40,959 --> 00:41:43,661
because she had to rewrite the conversation

671
00:41:43,661 --> 00:41:46,083
with Vera Markovic in the first limb clinic

672
00:41:46,083 --> 00:41:46,684
for the third time.

673
00:41:46,684 --> 00:41:47,505
Balancing and debug.

674
00:41:47,505 --> 00:41:48,205
How did we balance this game?

675
00:42:02,011 --> 00:42:07,298
The first thing we decided upon was to balance the critical path independently from the exploration

676
00:42:07,298 --> 00:42:08,199
path.

677
00:42:08,199 --> 00:42:13,285
So the first thing is we made sure that on the critical path, if you did not explore,

678
00:42:13,285 --> 00:42:16,750
you would get enough stuff to get through the game.

679
00:42:16,750 --> 00:42:18,632
And everything else was gravy.

680
00:42:19,990 --> 00:42:24,453
We used these balance boards to get a sense of everything that was in the game.

681
00:42:24,453 --> 00:42:27,315
This is about half the boards we had. We had six in total.

682
00:42:27,315 --> 00:42:32,539
And the reason we used boards is because the metric system wasn't working.

683
00:42:32,539 --> 00:42:36,262
We had one, but it broke down and we didn't have time to fix it

684
00:42:36,262 --> 00:42:39,565
before we had to finish the game and finish the balancing.

685
00:42:39,565 --> 00:42:45,849
I did the first pass at balancing using just an Excel sheet that rested on my computer.

686
00:42:46,510 --> 00:42:49,891
And if I remember correctly, it was a total failure.

687
00:42:49,891 --> 00:42:53,432
There was about 10 times too much ammo in the game.

688
00:42:53,432 --> 00:42:55,532
It was hard to balance the game

689
00:42:55,532 --> 00:42:56,993
without having something visual,

690
00:42:56,993 --> 00:43:00,534
something that would give me a big picture of what went on.

691
00:43:00,534 --> 00:43:02,915
So after doing a first pass that was a failure,

692
00:43:02,915 --> 00:43:05,535
play tests showed us that people were just

693
00:43:05,535 --> 00:43:07,376
gunning everything, they weren't thinking.

694
00:43:07,376 --> 00:43:09,416
It was just a huge frag fest.

695
00:43:10,993 --> 00:43:15,658
So we use these boards, and then again because we didn't have metrics, the only way to actually

696
00:43:15,658 --> 00:43:20,922
know what was in the game was to go in the editor, open every single level, every single

697
00:43:20,922 --> 00:43:24,686
inventory, every single shop, and then pin stuff to the wall.

698
00:43:28,153 --> 00:43:34,577
But doing that, we knew exactly then how much ammo was in the game, how much experience points,

699
00:43:34,577 --> 00:43:40,279
how much, well, pretty much everything. Grenades and whatever practice kits.

700
00:43:40,279 --> 00:43:45,682
And we could also see trends. We could see where we were giving out too much experience.

701
00:43:45,682 --> 00:43:50,385
We could visually see where do we give the laser rifle for the first time.

702
00:43:50,385 --> 00:43:56,788
Or what's the featured weapon in this map or this other map.

703
00:43:57,286 --> 00:44:02,969
So it was a really, really useful tool and it's only after we did the balance boards

704
00:44:02,969 --> 00:44:07,311
that the game really started to take shape in terms of balancing.

705
00:44:07,311 --> 00:44:13,654
The other thing I learned about balancing this game was that, as I said, we put in too

706
00:44:13,654 --> 00:44:16,715
much ammo at the beginning and then we drastically reduced everything.

707
00:44:16,715 --> 00:44:19,116
We removed a lot of stuff.

708
00:44:20,081 --> 00:44:22,183
And during playtests, people would complain.

709
00:44:22,183 --> 00:44:24,304
They would say, well, I don't have enough ammo

710
00:44:24,304 --> 00:44:26,046
to kill everybody.

711
00:44:26,046 --> 00:44:28,528
But then again, that's exactly what we wanted.

712
00:44:28,528 --> 00:44:31,891
The first time people went into the manufacturing plant

713
00:44:31,891 --> 00:44:35,914
and they emptied their combat rifle during the first combat,

714
00:44:35,914 --> 00:44:36,715
they understood.

715
00:44:37,206 --> 00:44:40,108
at that time, exactly what the game was about,

716
00:44:40,108 --> 00:44:42,610
and that it wasn't a game for you to just run and gun.

717
00:44:42,610 --> 00:44:44,932
It was a game for you to hide and think

718
00:44:44,932 --> 00:44:47,654
and check out your inventory and your augmentations

719
00:44:47,654 --> 00:44:51,598
to find out, to actually explore

720
00:44:51,598 --> 00:44:53,639
and find other ways to get through challenges.

721
00:44:53,639 --> 00:44:55,721
And that's where the fun lies.

722
00:44:55,721 --> 00:44:57,663
At the beginning, when there was a lot of ammo,

723
00:44:57,663 --> 00:45:00,065
people thought, well, the game is fun, but...

724
00:45:00,485 --> 00:45:04,527
It's okay, nothing much, but as soon as we removed and we toned it down a lot,

725
00:45:04,527 --> 00:45:08,408
the fun factor went through the roof instantly.

726
00:45:08,408 --> 00:45:09,449
People were liking it.

727
00:45:09,449 --> 00:45:13,931
Yeah, they were bitching at the beginning, but that's because they did not understand the game.

728
00:45:13,931 --> 00:45:15,751
They were new to the franchise.

729
00:45:15,751 --> 00:45:20,473
But afterwards, once they got through the first part of the level, they really liked it.

730
00:45:20,473 --> 00:45:24,815
They really thought this is new, this is something, there's strategy behind it.

731
00:45:24,815 --> 00:45:28,037
I got a thinking, thank you for that.

732
00:45:28,037 --> 00:45:29,237
They were really happy about it.

733
00:45:33,117 --> 00:45:33,578
Conclusion.

734
00:45:33,578 --> 00:45:34,879
So in conclusion.

735
00:45:41,902 --> 00:45:45,463
What I learned during Human Revolution is that there is no magic recipe.

736
00:45:45,463 --> 00:45:46,663
It takes a lot of work.

737
00:45:46,663 --> 00:45:49,904
It also takes people that you like working with.

738
00:45:49,904 --> 00:45:54,065
We were a tight-knit group and we still are.

739
00:45:54,065 --> 00:45:57,806
We have confidence in each other and we like working together.

740
00:45:57,806 --> 00:46:00,707
I think that shows in the final game.

741
00:46:00,707 --> 00:46:02,747
You also got to follow your gut.

742
00:46:02,747 --> 00:46:04,968
You got to pour yourself in what you're doing.

743
00:46:04,968 --> 00:46:11,290
We lived and breathed their sex for a long time, a lot of years.

744
00:46:12,580 --> 00:46:15,582
Also, God of faith is the truth. You're not perfect.

745
00:46:15,582 --> 00:46:18,805
We made a lot of mistakes and people would tell us,

746
00:46:18,805 --> 00:46:22,087
this is not working, and we had to listen to them.

747
00:46:22,087 --> 00:46:24,509
And we had to correct these mistakes.

748
00:46:24,509 --> 00:46:28,251
We could have decided, no, no, we don't want to hear anything.

749
00:46:29,523 --> 00:46:30,824
that would have been a problem.

750
00:46:30,824 --> 00:46:33,947
The game wouldn't be as good as it is right now.

751
00:46:33,947 --> 00:46:35,348
It's because we listened to people.

752
00:46:35,348 --> 00:46:36,890
It's because everybody had a say.

753
00:46:36,890 --> 00:46:39,052
Everybody was kind of equal on the team.

754
00:46:39,052 --> 00:46:42,015
And you also gotta question yourself.

755
00:46:42,015 --> 00:46:45,138
You really gotta look at what you're doing.

756
00:46:45,138 --> 00:46:48,341
Like hacking, I wasn't questioning myself.

757
00:46:48,341 --> 00:46:50,723
I had a vision.

758
00:46:50,723 --> 00:46:53,005
I really wanted to create something.

759
00:46:53,005 --> 00:46:54,887
I had an agenda, and that was a problem.

760
00:46:55,493 --> 00:47:01,800
I wasn't thinking about the overall game, I was thinking about me being finally a designer

761
00:47:01,800 --> 00:47:06,064
that creates this totally awesome hacking gameplay.

762
00:47:06,064 --> 00:47:10,328
And it turned out that it was my... it was a good lesson for me, actually.

763
00:47:12,085 --> 00:47:17,107
And finally, the last thing I learned was work for a company that has trust in you.

764
00:47:17,107 --> 00:47:20,368
Deus Ex was a huge endeavor.

765
00:47:20,368 --> 00:47:24,230
It was very complex to do, but still the company was always behind us.

766
00:47:24,230 --> 00:47:31,093
And I think it was very important because had we had somebody constantly second-guessing

767
00:47:31,093 --> 00:47:36,556
everything we did, or just coming in and saying, I'm not sure about this, and I'm not sure

768
00:47:36,556 --> 00:47:40,838
about that, we wouldn't have been able to do the game that we did.

769
00:47:42,145 --> 00:47:43,987
So I thank you very much, thank you for coming.

770
00:47:43,987 --> 00:47:58,939
If there are any questions, please use the mics.

771
00:48:08,087 --> 00:48:21,358
Hi, so I was interested in hearing with you guys how you guys approach the cameras in the game for Deus Ex and Revolutions because in the original Deus Ex I used them a lot as tools during my gameplay to point and look at where I was going to see some of my objectives.

